 and in the process he gains insights into patriarchy, class, sex, gender, and the challenges these women face. Combining oral history with magical realism and poetry, Honeypot is an engaging and moving book that reveals the complexity of identity while offering a creative method for scholarship to represent the lives of other people in a rich and dynamic way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican American lesbianszSouthern StatesvBiography. 0aAfrican American lesbianszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican American lesbianszSouthern StatesxHistoryy21st century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478007241zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478007241423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478007241.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles